IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
On June 28, 2023 I, DFC. Miller of the Queen Anne's County Sheriff's Office, currently assigned to the Queen Anne's County Drug Task Force, opened a criminal investigation into the possible drug distribution occurring in Stevensville, Maryland.  

Case to remain open pending further investigation.

On October 4, 2023, at approximately 0848 hours I, DFC. Miller of the Queen Anne's County Sheriff's Office, currently assigned to the Queen Anne's County Drug Task Force executed a search and seizure warrant at 400 Main Street Stevensville, Queen Anne's County, Maryland 21666.  I was assisted by other Task Force personnel from Queen Anne's and Caroline County as well as uniformed personnel from Queen Anne's County Sheriff's, Maryland State Police and Natural Resource Police.  The warrant was for William White Snyder Jr. and his residence.  Upon arrival to 400 Main Street, I observed Snyder as well as his girlfriend, identified as Alyssa Marie Turner, sitting on the front porch of the residence with two children.  When Snyder left the residence to place the kids on the school bus, Task Force personnel as well as Queen Anne's County Sheriff's SWAT team, made an approach to the residence and detained Snyder and Turner without confrontation.  All occupants were handcuffed after stating that they had no injuries and denied medical attention.  I provided Snyder with a copy of the search and seizure warrant and read him all the commands provided in the scope of the warrants and explained them to him.       

     A detailed search of the residence revealed the following items:

Item 1: One plastic baggie containing a white powder substance of suspected cocaine located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 2: One dollar bill containing a white powder substance of suspected cocaine located in Snyder's bedroom.
Item 3: Black glass square containing a white powder residue, suspected cocaine, located in Snyder's bedroom.
Item 4: Clear glass square containing a white powder residue, suspected cocaine, located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 5: Orange working digital scale, containing a white powder residue, suspected cocaine, located in Snyder's bedroom.   
Item 6: Plastic heat sealed bag containing suspected cocaine residue and four plastic baggie knots, located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 7: One plastic baggie containing a white powder substance, suspected cocaine, located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 8: One plastic baggie containing a white powder substance, suspected cocaine, located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 9: Two razor blades containing a white powder residue, suspected cocaine, located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 10: $60.00 in U.S. currency located in Snyder's bedroom.  
Item 11: Burnt metal spoon containing a white powder residue, suspected cocaine and a box of unused plastic baggies located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 12: Silver Ipad located on Snyder's bed. 
Item 13: ZOSI HD Digital recorder camera system located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 14: Mail addressed to William Snyder at 400 Main Street, located in Snyder's bedroom. 
Item 15: Short, cut straw containing a white powder residue, suspected cocaine located in a cigarette pack in Turner's purse. 
Item 16: One dollar bill containing a white powder substance, suspected cocaine, located in a cigarette pack in Turner's purse. 
Item 17: One black Samsung cellphone located in Snyder's pocket.

     The above-mentioned seized items were later taken to the Queen Anne's County Drug Task Force for processing.  Item number 1, 2,7 and 8 were located on a shelf in a bedroom identified as Snyder's.  Item number 1 weighed .9 grams with packaging, item number 2 weighed 1.9 grams with packaging, item number 7 weighed 11.3 grams with packaging and item number 8 weighed 1.5 grams with packaging for a total weight of 15.6 grams of cocaine.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that this amount is consistent with an amount for distribution.  I know that the average user with consume approximately around 1 or 2 grams of cocaine in week.  The amount of suspected cocaine located has a street value of approximately $1,500.00, and I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that the average user will only purchase an amount of cocaine to be used within a short time period, due to the fear of having a large amount and losing it or it being stolen from them.  Item number 3 and 4 consisted of glass pieces containing cocaine residue.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that these items are commonly used to prepare a controlled dangerous substance to be ingested through the nostril.  Item number 5 consisted of a working digital scale that contained cocaine residue.  Drug dealers will commonly possess a scale in order to weigh product that is to be packaged for sale.  This scale is used to maximize profits with an accurate weight.  Item number 9 consisted of two razor blades that contained cocaine residue.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that razor blades are commonly used to prepare a controlled dangerous substance for consumption.  Item number 10 consisted of three $20.00 bills which were located next to the cocaine that was found, suspected to be proceeds from controlled dangerous substance sales.  Item number 11 consisted of a metal spoon that contained cocaine residue as well as burn marks on the bottom side.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that this spoon is used to prepare and consume a controlled dangerous substance but heating the bottom of the spoon and inhaling/injecting the substance in the spoon.  Item 12 consisted of an Ipad that was located on the bed of Snyder's bedroom.  This item was returned to Tuner.  Item number 13 consisted of a camera system that was placed around the inside and outside the residence.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that drug dealers will use cameras to monitor the residence to prevent theft of product and/or to observe when costumers arrive to purchase an amount of substance.  Item number 14 consisted of mail that was addressed to Snyder, located in the bedroom.  Item 17 is described as a black Samsung cellular phone located on Snyder's persons.  I will be authoring a search and seizure warrant for this cellular phone at a later date.  All of these items were located in a bedroom that was identified as Snyder's room. 
     Item number 15 and 16 were located in Turner's purse with belongings that identified this purse as hers.  Item number 15 consisted of a short, cut straw containing cocaine residue which I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that this straw is used to inhale a controlled dangerous substance through way of the nostril.  Item number 16 consisted of a dollar bill that contained suspected cocaine in the amount of 2.1 grams.  I will be completing an Application for Charges on Turner at a later date.      
     The following items were seized and held under property held P-345818:
Item 1: One plastic baggie containing a white powder substance suspected cocaine.  Weight: .9 grams with packaging.
Item 2: One dollar bill containing a white power substance suspected cocaine.  Weight: 1.9 grams with packaging.
Item 3: Black square glass containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine.  Weight: Trace.
Item 4: Clear square glass containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine.  Weight: Trace.
Item 5: One orange digital scale containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine.  Weight: Trace.
Item 6: One heat sealed bag containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine.  Weight: Trace.
Item 6A: Four plastic baggie knots containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine.  Weight: Trace.
Item 7: One plastic baggie containing a white powder substance suspected cocaine.  Weight: 11.3 grams with packaging.
Item 8: One plastic baggie containing a white powder substance suspected cocaine.  Weight: 1.5 grams with packaging.
Item 9: Two razor blades containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine.  Weight: Trace.
Item 11: One metal spoon with burn on the bottom containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine and a box of unused plastic baggies.  Weight: Trace. 
     The following items were seized and held under property held P-345819:
Item 15: One short, cut straw containing a white powder residue suspected cocaine.  Weight: Trace.
Item 16: One dollar bill containing a white powder substance suspected cocaine.  Weight: 2.1 grams with packaging.  
     Items 1,2,5,7, 8, 15 and 16 will be sent to Maryland State Police Crime Lab in order to be properly tested for the presence of a controlled dangerous substance.  
     The search warrant and return were given to Snyder.  I explained the items seized, and he signed the return.  Snyder was placed under arrest and taken to Maryland State Police Centreville Barrack for processing.  While at the barracks, I advised Snyder that if he would like to speak, I would advise him of his Miranda Rights.  Snyder advised that he wished to talk and was read his rights at 1000 hours at which time he acknowledged that he understood his rights and signed the Advice of Miranda Rights form.  Snyder advised that he mainly sells to support his own habit and that he had become complacent in what he was doing.  Snyder was then charged with the following:
CDS: Possession with intent to distribute.
CDS: Possession-not cannabis.
CDS: Possession paraphernalia.
CDS: Possession paraphernalia.
     Snyder was taken before the Queen Anne's County District Court Commissioner and was released on $10,000 unsecured bond.
     While attending the Eastern Shore Criminal Justice Academy, I received training in the identification and recognition of CDS to include cocaine and how it is manufactured, packaged, priced, transported and ingested.  I know from my training, knowledge and experience that the individual baggies of a white substance, is consistent with prepackaging of controlled dangerous substance for sale at a later date.  I know from my training, knowledge and experience that the working digital scale is used to weigh an amount of CDS prior to resale.  This is done in an effort to maximize profit.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that the box of empty baggies are used to prepackage an amount of CDS for sale at a later date.  I have been a police officer for over 6 years and have arrested numerous persons for CDS violations and have seen these persons convicted in both District and Circuit Courts.     
      
I request this case remain open pending the download of Snyder's cellular phone as well as the service of Turner's charges.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
During the search and seizure warrant served on October 4, 2023, for the residence and persons of William White Snyder, I, DFC Joey Miller, recovered a Samsung cellular phone belonging to Snyder. 
     Based off of my investigation leading up to the search warrant and the amount of drugs I located from Snyder's residence I believed the Samsung phone contained call, logs, text messages and other electronic evidence indicating Snyder's involvement into the distribution of controlled dangerous substances in Queen Anne's County, Maryland.
   On October 16, 2023, I applied for and received a search and seizure warrant through the District Court for Queen Anne's County, Maryland to examine digital information on the phone from the time period of July 4, 2023, through the date of seizure on October 4, 2023. This warrant was reviewed and signed by Judge Kratovil.  After receiving the search and seizure warrant, I had the phone  extracted by Cpl. Buckius of the Queen Anne's County Drug Task Force.
   I reviewed and provided to the State's Attorney's Office, in paper format, only the information recovered for the time frame between July 4, 2023, through October 4, 2023. I also provided the information recovered in electronic format.
  The following conversations were located throughout the Samsung Cellular phone that Snyder claimed was his:

18481 +14104907436 * Clough Eric 30/09/2023 13:37:54 (GMT-4)   Sent Sent Phone Outgoing Yup
     
     During this conversation, Clough is asking Snyder if he is home in which Snyder replies that he is.  Clough replies to Snyder advising that he is coming from Centreville and ask if he can get "2".  Snyder replies "yup".  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience, that during this conversation Clough wants 2 grams of a controlled dangerous substance and that he will be in route get it.  Snyder acknowledges this request.

18282 +14103107680 * New Jukebox 29/09/2023 18:28:55 (GMT-4)   Sent Sent Phone Outgoing Ok got it

     During this conversation, Jukebox is letting Snyder know that he is on his way "40 and 40".  Snyder replies, "do what" and Jukebox replies that he is going to pay Snyder 40 and get a 40.  Snyder acknowledges.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that based on the conversation Jukebox owes Snyder $40, but he also wants $40 worth of a controlled dangerous substance as well.   
18230 +14104901258 * Loetz Mike 29/09/2023 16:01:37 (GMT-4) +19039321429 Read Inbox Phone Incoming Just leaving work I have everything that I owe you. Can I grab a 150
18231 +14104901258 * Loetz Mike 29/09/2023 16:02:04 (GMT-4)   Sent Sent Phone Outgoing I will let you know when I get home
18232 +14104901258 * Loetz Mike 29/09/2023 16:08:25 (GMT-4) +19039321428 Read Inbox Phone Incoming Yup
18233 +14104901258 * Loetz Mike 29/09/2023 16:10:41 (GMT-4)   Sent Sent Phone Outgoing Running errands
 
     During this conversation, Mike is advising Snyder that he has everything he owes him and would like to grab a 150.  Snyder replies that he will let him know when he gets home because he is running errands.  Based on the conversation, I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that Mike is going to be paying Snyder money that he owes and would also like to buy $150 worth of a controlled dangerous substance.  


     I also located a photograph in the photo album of this cellular phone.  I know based on my training, knowledge and experience that the above picture depicts an amount of controlled dangerous substance in a plastic baggie.  I also know based on my training, knowledge and experience that the razor blade containing the white powder residue, is commonly used to prepare an amount of controlled dangerous substance for consumption.  

      Based on the above conversations located throughout Snyder's cellular phone, I believe based on my training, knowledge and experience, that Snyder is participating in the distribution of narcotics in the Queen Anne's County, Maryland area.

While conducting a detailed search of the cellular phone, identified as belonging to WIlliam Snyder Jr., I located evidence of possible child pornography.  I contacted the Criminal Investigations Unit at the Queen Anne's County Sheriff's and advised them of what was found.  After reviewing the photograph that was located stored on the cellular phone, CIU opened a separate case on Snyder.  

     On October 19, 2023, the Queen Anne's County Sheriff's served Alyssa Turner with a Summons for the possession of a controlled dangerous substance. 

I request this case be closed.
